Parse glsl files with windows carriage returns

Ran into an upstream failure in stackgl/headless-gl
when parsing preprocessor lines with windows carriage
returns (\r\n).

This adds a test case, and fixes it in two possible 
ways:
1. replace all \r with \n before parsing, or
2. on the preprocessor line, end at \r or \n.

The second fix is the smallest possible fix for the
issue I was running into. But the first fix seems like
a more general solution.

Modify behavior of 'namespace' in the router:

* :namespace as an option to resources does not modify the matched url path
* r.namespace lets you pass in a :path option to specify what gets matched for the url path

          admin.resources :posts
        end

bldr function requires a key.


By adding the key to the bldr function, we can separate usages
in a simple fashion.

commit_list.message:
Conditional queries for include,>,extends,block:

For these tags, we might want to pass in a string
literal, or lookup something on the context. If
we prefix our key with a #, it will use context
lookup, otherwise, it will be a string literal.

Tags that don't make sense with a string literal
(#,if,stamp) do not require the # prefix.

So:
.# content blog/first-post
  .< {_type}
./#

Would render a partial named with the content
object's type; (eg: 'post')

This lets us do some dynamic rendering that is
not possible with just string literals.

commit_list.message:
Add queryCache support: cache api requests on the server

This lets you avoid the double api request problem, where
a model or collection would be fetched when rendering on 
the server, and again when the app is initialized on the
client.

By outputting the queryCache into the server side rendered
page, and reinitializing the queryCache on app initialization,
that double fetch will be prevented, and the app initialization
will be sped up.

commit_list.message:
Server side multi user backbone models, v0.0.16

Backbone models use a singleton for 
communication with the server. This works 
perfectly fine on the client (browser), where
only one user may be logged in. However, on the
server, it is possible that different backbone
model instances should belong to different users.

This commit extends both Model and Collection with
an 'init' static method. The first parameter
to init is an object that is used to extend the
request on the server.

Thus, to authenticate the request:

```js
var post = Post.init({user: user}, {_id: '23'});
post.fetch({success: success});
```

commit_list.message:
Modify behavior of 'namespace' in the router:

* :namespace as an option to resources does not modify the matched url path
* r.namespace lets you pass in a :path option to specify what gets matched for the url path
    ex. r.namespace(:admin, :path=>"") do |admin|
          admin.resources :posts
        end

    will now match "/posts", and not "/admin/posts", but still pass on namespace in the params
